<subSubSection pageId="105" pageNumber="501" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="105.[724,1321,1323,1745]" lastBlockId="105.[115,1321,1753,2418]" pageId="105" pageNumber="501">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[729,979,1712,1745]" pageId="105" pageNumber="501">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 63-68 mm, tail 53-56 mm. No specific data are available for body weight. The Serezkaya Whitetoothed Shrew is medium-sized and lightly built. Tail is 75-85% of head-body length. Pelage is bicolored. Dorsum is silvery gray, with smoky blue tint in juveniles;silvery gray becomes brown-tinted in adults. Venter is pure white or grayish/bluish white. Tail is weakly bicolored (smoky or brownish gray above and off-white below) in juveniles and unicolored (grayish white on both sides) in adults.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[116,980,1990,2023]" pageId="105" pageNumber="501" type="biology_ecology">
